Introduction

Inspiration

Playing as a professional basketball player in the NBA is one of the all-time highest paying job, big-firms-owned teams have a huge capital dedicated to recruit and award some of the best talents in the world. But how much exactly do they make? This project we’re exploring the relationship between NBA players’ salary with some potential predictors, using the tool of linear regression models. Also, due to the large and complicated nature of sports data set, this project is also to showcase my data tidying ability to see how I can navigate my way through tedious data across decades.

I believe there must exist some indicators that has relation with NBA player salaries. Some player makes tens of millions a year , while some of the more “unlucky” ones make some hundred thousands a year (I know, it’s still alot). According to my knowledge form watching years of basketball and basic knowledge of economics, I have concludes three predictors that potentially have correlation to an NBA players salary, which is year/season they play in, the market size of the city of the team they play for, and their on-court performance.

To break these three component apart, the year takes a numeric value, indicating the calender year when the season starts (that’s pretty intuitive). The city size takes discrete variable, taking values from “big”, “medium”, and “small”, for example, the Los Angeles Lakers ,located in Los Angeles, would be a “big” city, and the Memphis Grizzlies, located in Memphis, would be a “small city”. Finally, the player’s on-court performance, this is the most complicated variable since there is numerous statistics to determine if a player is a “good” player or not, the offensive attribute tend to reflect more directly in statistics, while leadership quality and defensive ability doesn’t reflect in stats sheet as well. Therefore, I chose two indicators that represents a player’s performance to cover these two aspects, which are their points per game average for the past three years, and their net rating for the past three years. The reason why I want to take the average from the past three years is because a players salary this year is heavily depend on their past performances, generally you have to “prove” that you’re a good player before yo sign a big contract. The details of these statistic will be provided in the following sections.

Data Description and Sources

First we load the data set and check its quality. I’ve gathered three datasets from two different sources:

  • Kaggle, NBA Players Performance and Salaries, The Devastator

    This dataset provides a comprehensive look at NBA player salaries and performance from 1985 to 2018. It contains two data frames with detailed records of salary figures, season information, physical attributes (such as height and weight), draft information, college attended, career stats (including points scored and win shares) and shooting hand preference. From this data set, I will be utilizing the salaries, player name, years played, and team information. link here

  • Kaggle, NBA Players, Justina Cirtautas

    The data set on Kaggle contains over two decades of data on each player who has been part of an NBA teams’ roster, with the time frame spanning from 1996-2022. It captures demographic variables such as age, height, weight and place of birth, biographical details like the team played for, draft year and round. In addition, it has basic box score statistics such as games played, average number of points, rebounds, assists, etc. From this data set I will be taking the players’ name, team, ppg and +/- for each year. Also since this data set’s time frame doesn’t perfectly overlap with NBA Players Performance and Salaries, I will be investigating the time period where two data sets overlaps, which is from 1996-2018. link here

  • HoopSocials.com, NBA Team Market Size Rankings, Michael Burns

    This is not a data set, but works as an additional source to help classify teams sizes into categories big, medium, and small. HoopsSocials.com is a media platform focusing on sports news and collecting sports data, specifically in basketball and about leagues like NBA and WNBA. I will be using the classification provided in this website to help me determine and classify the scale of an NBA team, as I believe that the market size of an NBA team will be an effective predictor of an NBA player’s salary. Additionally, since the website only covers cities that currently has NBA teams, for those city in the data frame that previously have NBA teams, I will refer to this page from sportsmedia.com and put them in the category where their market size matches the best. link here

Cleaning the Salary Data Set

Now, let’s start to extract the data we need from our data set. First, let’s work with the salary_player_info and salary_salary to get the players’ name, team, year when season started, and most importantly, their salary. We’re also going to create a column of abbreviations of team names for easier comparison moving forward.

#combine salary_player_info and salary_salary by player_id
salary_full = salary_player_info_full %>% 
  left_join(salary_salary_full, by = c("X_id"="player_id"))

#add a column of team abbreviations
salary_full = salary_full %>% 
  mutate(team_abv = case_when(
    team %in% names(team_abbreviations) ~ team_abbreviations[team],
    TRUE ~ NA_character_
  ))

Furthermore, since we’re working on observations between 1996 and 2018, and the smallest contract a player can sign in 1996 is 248000 per year. Also, the amount of a minimum contract strictly increased over the years, so any number smaller than 248000 will be viewed as an error from the data collecting process and will be dropped as well.

#drop rows with salaries less than 248000
salary_full = salary_full %>% 
  filter(salary >= 248000)

Finally, extract the columns we need for the purpose of this project.

#extract only the columns we need from salary_full
salary = salary_full %>% 
  select(name, salary, team, team_abv, season_start)

Cleaning the Player Info Data Set

Now let’s work with the player_info_full dataframe and extract the variables we need, which includes name, team, points per game(ppg), net rating, and year when season started. Keep in mind here, for the season variable were getting two years value, ex. 1998-99. We need to do some manipulation so that the variable only contains the year when season started, ex. 1998.

#create a column season_start denoting the year when season starts
player_info_full = player_info_full %>% 
  mutate(season_start = as.integer(substr(season, 1, 4)))

Also, we’re creating an extra column, ppt_avg_3, denoting the previous three years’ point per game average, so for a player’s ppt_avg_3 in 2019, we would take the average of his pts in 2016-2018, if there’s not enough data in previous years, we’ll take the average of the available pts(2017-2018 or 2018), if there’s no data in previous years, we’ll just take the corresponding year’s pts (2019).

#create the column ppg_avg_3 denoting the average of points per game for the past three years.
player_info_full = player_info_full %>% 
  arrange(player_name, season_start) %>% 
  group_by(player_name) %>% 
  mutate(pts_lag1 = dplyr::lag(pts), pts_lag2 = dplyr::lag(pts, 2),
         pts_lag3 = dplyr::lag(pts, 3),
         ppg_avg_3 = case_when(
           !is.na(pts_lag3) ~ (pts_lag1 + pts_lag2 + pts_lag3)/3,
           !is.na(pts_lag2) ~ (pts_lag1 + pts_lag2)/2,
           !is.na(pts_lag1) ~ (pts_lag1)/1,
           .default = pts,
           )) %>% 
  ungroup()

Furthermore, with the same idea of moving average, we’re taking the past three year average for the net_rating variable, call it net_avg_3. I observed that if a player has very few games played in a season, the net_rating can be very falsely representing the player’s performance. Therefore, we’re dropping players if they played no more than 5 games in a 82 game season (You’re basically not an NBA player that year if you played no more than 5 games in a season).

#create the column net_avg_3 denoting the average of points per game for the past three years.
player_info_full = player_info_full %>% 
  arrange(player_name, season_start) %>% 
  group_by(player_name) %>% 
  mutate(net_lag1 = dplyr::lag(net_rating), net_lag2 = dplyr::lag(net_rating, 2),
         net_lag3 = dplyr::lag(net_rating, 3),
         net_avg_3 = case_when(
           !is.na(net_lag3) ~ (net_lag1 + net_lag2 + net_lag3)/3,
           !is.na(net_lag2) ~ (net_lag1 + net_lag2)/2,
           !is.na(net_lag1) ~ (net_lag1)/1,
           .default = net_rating,
           )) %>% 
  ungroup()

# drop all rows with gp no more than 5 
player_info_full = player_info_full %>% 
  filter(gp > 5)

#check the output of both ppg_avg_3 and net_avg_3
temp = player_info_full %>% 
  select(player_name, pts, ppg_avg_3, net_rating, net_avg_3, season_start)

Create Predictor: Market Size

Let’s combine the salary and player_info data sets.

#combine data sets salary and player_info
NBA_salary = salary %>% 
  left_join(player_info, by = c("name" = "player_name", "season_start" = "season_start"))

## ℹ Row 9297 of `y` matches multiple rows in `x`.
## ℹ If a many-to-many relationship is expected, set `relationship =
##   "many-to-many"` to silence this warning.

There’s a clear observations, if a player switched teams during the season, salary$team_abv documents the team the player start the team with, while player_info$team_abbreviation has the team the player plays for after the season ends. Since the salary a player earns should be more based on the team the player starts his season with, I’m going to drop the column team_abbreviation to closely represent the data and to prevent confusion when fitting the model.

#drop the column team_abbreviation
NBA_salary = NBA_salary %>% 
  select(-team_abbreviation)

Now, let’s create a column denoting the market size of the team, the classification will be based on the source sites in the previous section. For teams “SEA”, “NJN,”NOH”, “NOK”, “VAN”, since these are not current teams, I either put them into the same categories with teams located at the same city, or relied outside source (Google search) to determine the market size of these teams.

#create a list that maps teams to their market sizes
team_size_mapping = list(
  big_teams = c("NYK", "BKN", "NJN", "LAL", "LAC", "CHI", "PHI", "DAL", "TOR", "GSW", "ATL", "HOU", "WAS", "BOS", "PHO"), 
  medium_teams = c("SEA", "MIN", "DET", "DEN", "ORL", "MIA", "CLE"), 
  small_teams = c("SAC", "POR", "CHA", "IND", "UTH", "SAS", "MIL", "OKC", "NOP", "NOH", "NOK", "MEM", "VAN")
)

#create a column denoting the market size of the team
NBA_salary = NBA_salary %>% 
  mutate(team_size = case_when(
    team_abv %in% team_size_mapping$big_teams ~ "big",
    team_abv %in% team_size_mapping$medium_teams ~ "medium", 
    team_abv %in% team_size_mapping$small_teams ~ "small", 
    TRUE ~ NA_character_
  ))

Describing the Predictors

Now that we have cleaned up and obtain the data set we needed, let’s introduce the desciption of these variables before we go to the next step:

  • name: The name of the NBA player (ex. Lebron James, Kobe Bryant)
  • salary: The salary of the NBA player given the year he played in
  • season_start: The calander year when the season started (ranging from 1996 to 2018)
  • team_size: The market size of the NBA team based on the city located (either big, mudium or small)
  • ppg_avg_3: The averge points per game of the player’s past three years’ performance. If the player only has one or two previous years’ data, then take the average of those years. If the player has no prior years of data, then take the current year’s points per game.
  • net_avg_3: Team’s point differential per 100 possessions while the player is on the court. Miving average calculated the same way as ppg_avg_3

We’ve defined all the variables in our data set. Moving forward, we’re going to do some exploratory data analysis and take a deeper look comprehensively about our data.

Model Fitting

Fitting Linear Regression Model

Now, let’s fit our data in a linear regression model. Since the predictor team_size is categorical, we first create dummy variables and then use the dummy variables to fit in the model

#drop the name column as it is irrelevant to the purpose of this project
NBA_salary_no_name = NBA_salary %>% 
  select(-name)

#create dummy variables
dummy_vars = model.matrix(~ team_size - 1, data = NBA_salary_no_name)  # Exclude intercept term with '- 1'

#combine dummy variables with original data
NBA_salary_with_dummy = NBA_salary_no_name %>% 
  cbind(dummy_vars) %>% 
  select(-team_size)

#fit linear regression model
lm_NBA_salary = lm(salary ~ ., data = NBA_salary_with_dummy)

#print the summary of the linear model
summary(lm_NBA_salary)

From the summary of our linear model, observe and conclude that season_start, ppg_avg_3, net_avg_3 all have significant positive effect on a players annual salary. In short, the if a player is more recent, scores more, or have a great net rating, they are expected to have more income than those that fall short in these predictor variables. However, the market size of the team, team_size, doesn’t play as big of a role in deciding a players wage and it’s effect is not significant.

Also, the R-squared of the model is 0.5318, which is over 0.5, indicating that linear regression explains a good amount of variability of the data. To further analyze our result, let’s make some visualizations of the fitted model and the data set.

For the variables that are significant predictors, I’ve created visualization and comparison of the case if we fit regression with raw data and the case when we take the log value and some linear transformation of the predictors (particularly, taking square root of ppg_avg_3). We can see that, for predictors season_start and ppg_avg_3, after the transformation, linear regression seemed to be a pretty good predicting model. But for predictor net_avg_3, maybe we need some other transformation to better fit the linear transformation model, or perhaps we should use other type of models.

Now lets look at the residuals and fitted values plot

#residuals and fitted values plot
residuals = residuals(lm_NBA_salary)
fitted_values = fitted(lm_NBA_salary)

plot(fitted_values, residuals)

This is not a perfect shape of a residual plot as there is clear trend and lack of randomness of the residual plot. Form what the previous sections suggested, a useful solution can be taking log of the salary values. Furthermore, since taking the square root of ppg_avg_3 gives a shape closer to a normal distribution, we will take the square root of the ppg_avg_3 predictor as well. In the next section, we will try to fit the linear regression model again, but after linear transformations of variables.

Fitting Linear Regression Model with Linear-Transformed Variables

#taking the square root of ppg_avg_3 and replace the original variable
NBA_salary_with_dummy = NBA_salary_with_dummy %>% 
  mutate(sqrt_ppg_avg_3 = sqrt(ppg_avg_3)) %>% 
  select(-ppg_avg_3)

#fit linear regression model with logarithmic transformed response
lm_NBA_salary_log = lm(log(salary) ~ ., data = NBA_salary_with_dummy)

#print the summary of the linear model
summary(lm_NBA_salary_log)

However, I came to a new finding that team_size does have an significant effect on the salary’s log value. Actually, to my surprise, playing for a smaller team is the best for a player’s salary out of the three classes, following by playing for a big-sized team, and playing for a medium-sized team is actually worse for a player in terms of salary. Note that the R-squared value is .5274, which is still around the same level as before the transformation of variables is applied which is at a good level.

Check for Assumptions

In the last step of this project, we want to check the characteristics of our residuals to see if they match the assumptions of linear regressions. Particularly, we want to check the normality and homoscedasticity of residuals. First, we create the Q-Q plot to check for normality

#create the qqplot for the residuals
residuals = residuals(lm_NBA_salary_log)

qqnorm(residuals)
qqline(residuals, col = "red")

Even though the points don’t perfectly follow the line on both ends, the general trend of the dotted line does follow the qqline, suggesting that the residuals are normally distributed, we can also look at the histogram to see the distribution of the residuals.

hist(residuals, breaks = 50)

The histogram is a bell shaped curve, matching our initial conclusion, which is the residuals are normally distributed. Next, let’s revisit the residual plot after linear transformation of variables and check for homoscedasticity.

#residuals and fitted values plot
fitted_values = fitted(lm_NBA_salary_log)

plot(fitted_values, residuals)

The residual plot after the transformations definitely looks better than before the transformation is applied, but it still seems like there’s a trend in the residual plot, which for residuals to be homoscedastic the residual plot should be scattered without a recognizable trend. This suggests that further actions and investigations are needed, perhaps with a different transformation of variable or with a different model. Due to the scope and the purpose of this project, we will stop here until more advanced tools are provided in the future to better explain the data.
